<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-11-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-11-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="580" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d580">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Reid</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-11-22"><hi rend="italic">November 22,
                                    1906</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(No. 104. Sir Edward Grey writes Mr. Reid that his information in matter
                            has not gone beyond preparation of test cases which Mr. Root
                            anticipated, two men convicted under Bait Act and appealed, third to be
                            prosecuted for breach custom-house regulations. Sir Edward Grey was then
                            making further inquiries of colonial office, but hopes there will be no
                            practical interference actual working modus vivendi.)</p>
                    </div>
